episodes.title: EXCLUSIVE: Australian YouTuber being sued by Andrew Tate speaks out
episodes.description:
Analogue era parents who grew up with no exposure to social media are “completely incapable” of monitoring the negative impact of masculinity influencers such as Andrew Tate on their sons. 

That’s the warning from Adelaide YouTuber Nathan Pope who is among 13 people worldwide being sued for defamation by brothersAndrew and Tristan Tate for their campaign exposing the sinister workings of the Tates’ paid online portal “The Real World”. 

Here Nathan speaks exclusively with The Australian, about his ongoing case against Tate.

episodes.title: Scam or spirituality? Inside the power games of an Australian 'cult'
episodes.description:
Former members of a group that has offered high-priced enlightenment since the 1990s reveal the sex and power games at the heart of Access Consciousness. 

Gary Douglas used to sell houses. Now he sells self-improvement. He founded the ­Access Consciousness system – a confusing mix of the spiritual, the pragmatic and the ­impossible – in the early 1990s from his base in Santa Barbara, California. It was there that the former realtor began to forge a lucrative ­career peddling a form of energy therapy he said he learned by “channelling” – of all people – the Russian ­mystic Grigori Rasputin. Today, according to Access Consciousness, the group is active in 170 countries worldwide, with major centres in America, Ireland and Australia. Its local base is at Queensland’s Coolum Beach on the Sunshine Coast.

episodes.title: Access Consciousness Inside the cult taking over the world (WATCH)
episodes.description:
Former high-ranking members of global self-help organisation Access Consciousness have claimed one of the group’s male leadership figures “seduced” women who signed up for expensive alternative therapies that they were told would “clear limitations” in their lives.

Perth businesswoman Kerry Purcell, who spent 15 years working closely with senior leadership at Access Consciousness, has told The Weekend Australian that Access Consciousness co-creator Dain Heer “groomed” women to sleep with him and left them “shamed”, while also bullying those he saw as “competition”.

Here, Kerry Purcell and Margaret Braunack, who spent over a decade at Access Consciousness speak out about the organisation.
